                <h2>Scoring System Breakdown</h2>
                <p>
                    Your total score determines whether you get invited. The maximum is 200 points, distributed across several categories:
                </p>

                <h3>Personal Qualifications (Max 80 Points)</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Business/Management Experience:</strong> Up to 20 points for 10+ years of experience</li>
                    <li><strong>Business Ownership:</strong> Up to 16 points for 10+ years as a business owner</li>
                    <li><strong>Total Experience:</strong> Up to 24 points for combined management and ownership</li>
                    <li><strong>Education:</strong> Up to 12 points (PhD = 12, Master's = 10, Bachelor's = 8)</li>
                    <li><strong>Language Proficiency:</strong> Up to 8 points (CLB 8+ = 8 points)</li>
                </ul>

                <h3>Business Concept (Max 114 Points)</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Commercial Viability:</strong> Up to 30 points based on business plan quality</li>
                    <li><strong>Transferability:</strong> Up to 30 points (your experience matches the business)</li>
                    <li><strong>Economic Benefits:</strong> Up to 30 points (job creation, technology transfer, exports)</li>
                    <li><strong>Investment Amount:</strong> Up to 12 points (higher investment = more points)</li>
                    <li><strong>Regional Location:</strong> Up to 12 points bonus for Regional Pilot</li>
                </ul>

                <h3>Adaptability (Max 6 Points)</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Previous Legal Visit to Canada:</strong> 2 points</li>
                    <li><strong>Previous Business Trip to BC:</strong> 2 points</li>
                    <li><strong>Relatives in BC:</strong> 2 points</li>
                </ul>

                <h2>Success Factors</h2>
                <p>
                    Based on approved applications, these factors significantly improve your chances:
                </p>

                <h3>High-Impact Business Types</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Manufacturing:</strong> Businesses that produce goods locally score well</li>
                    <li><strong>Technology/Innovation:</strong> Software, clean tech, biotech</li>
                    <li><strong>Export-Oriented:</strong> Businesses that generate revenue from outside BC/Canada</li>
                    <li><strong>Tourism Development:</strong> Hotels, tour operations (especially in regional areas)</li>
                    <li><strong>Healthcare Services:</strong> Clinics, specialized medical services</li>
                    <li><strong>Agriculture Value-Add:</strong> Food processing, agri-tech (not hobby farms)</li>
                </ul>

                <h3>Documentation Excellence</h3>
                <p>
                    The most successful applicants provide extensive documentation:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Detailed market research with local competitor analysis</li>
                    <li>Professional financial projections (3-5 years)</li>
                    <li>Letters of intent from potential customers or suppliers</li>
                    <li>Real estate options or lease agreements</li>
                    <li>Organizational charts showing job creation plans</li>
                    <li>Exit strategy or succession planning</li>
                </ul>

                <h2>Common Reasons for Rejection</h2>
                <div class="bg-red-50 p-6 rounded-2xl border border-red-100 mb-6 not-prose">
                    <h4 class="font-bold text-red-900 mb-3">Why Applications Fail</h4>
                    <ul class="text-red-800 text-sm space-y-3">
                        <li>
                            <strong>1. Source of Funds Issues (40%):</strong> Cannot prove legal origin of all claimed assets, especially property sales, inheritance, or business profits from 5+ years ago.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <strong>2. Weak Business Viability (25%):</strong> Business plan lacks market research, unrealistic projections, or oversaturated market without differentiation strategy.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <strong>3. Experience Mismatch (20%):</strong> Proposed business doesn't align with applicant's background (e.g., IT manager proposing a restaurant).
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <strong>4. Interview Performance (10%):</strong> Cannot answer detailed questions about the business plan, location, or financial history.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <strong>5. Post-Arrival Non-Compliance (5%):</strong> Fails to meet Performance Agreement terms (investment amount, job creation, residency).
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h2>After Arrival: Performance Agreement</h2>
                <p>
                    Upon approval, you sign a legally binding Performance Agreement with BC PNP. This contract specifies:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Investment Timeline:</strong> When you must invest the committed funds</li>
                    <li><strong>Job Creation Goals:</strong> Number of jobs and timeline for hiring</li>
                    <li><strong>Residency Requirement:</strong> You must live in BC and be actively involved in the business</li>
                    <li><strong>Reporting Schedule:</strong> When to submit progress reports</li>
                    <li><strong>Final Report Deadline:</strong> Usually 18-20 months after arrival</li>
                </ul>

                <div class="bg-amber-50 p-6 rounded-2xl border border-amber-100 mb-6 not-prose">
                    <h4 class="font-bold text-amber-900 mb-2">Important Warning</h4>
                    <p class="text-amber-800 text-sm">
                        If you fail to meet your Performance Agreement terms, BC PNP will not nominate you for permanent residence. You may also be flagged for misrepresentation if the failure appears intentional. Some entrepreneurs have had to leave Canada after investing significant funds because they didn't meet job creation targets.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

                <h3>Can I bring a partner?</h3>
                <p>
                    In the <strong>Base Category only</strong>, you can propose
                    a "Key Staff" member (like a trusted manager) to come with
                    you. This increases the investment requirement to $400,000.
                    Regional Pilot does not allow Key Staff.
                </p>

                <h3>Is the language requirement strict?</h3>
                <p>
                    The minimum is <strong>CLB 4</strong> (basic proficiency). While
                    lower than skilled worker streams, you still need enough English
                    to run a business in BC.
                </p>

                <h3>What happens if my business fails?</h3>
                <p>
                    If you made a genuine effort, invested the money, and
                    operated for the required time but failed due to market
                    conditions, you <em>might</em> still be nominated. However, if
                    you failed to invest or shut down early, you will lose your nomination
                    chance.
                </p>

                <h3>Can I work for someone else while building my business?</h3>
                <p>
                    Your work permit is employer-specific to your own business. You cannot work for another employer. You must be actively involved in managing your business full-time.
                </p>

                <h3>How long does the entire process take?</h3>
                <p>
                    From initial registration to PR landing, expect <strong>3-5 years</strong>:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Registration to Invitation: 2-6 months</li>
                    <li>Application processing: 6-12 months</li>
                    <li>Net worth verification: 2-4 months</li>
                    <li>Interview scheduling: 1-3 months</li>
                    <li>Work permit processing: 2-4 months</li>
                    <li>Business operation period: 18-24 months</li>
                    <li>Final report review: 2-3 months</li>
                    <li>Federal PR processing: 12-18 months</li>
                </ul>
